<div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-center">Authentication: Verifying Who You Are</h1>

    <div class="beginner-note">
        <div class="beginner-note-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-fingerprint"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="beginner-note-content">
            <h4>Authentication is Like Showing Your ID</h4>
            <p>When you need to prove who you are in real life, you show your ID card or passport. Authentication is the digital version of this process.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Username/Password:</strong> Like showing your ID card</li>
                <li><strong>Email Confirmation:</strong> Like verifying your address on the ID</li>
                <li><strong>Two-Factor Authentication:</strong> Like also showing a second form of ID</li>
                <li><strong>Login Session:</strong> Like wearing a visitor badge that shows you're verified</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Simple definition:</strong> Authentication is the process of verifying that users are who they claim to be.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="important-note">
        <h4>The Good News: .NET Handles Authentication For You</h4>
        <p>When you create a new ASP.NET Core project and select "Individual Accounts" authentication, you get a complete, professional-grade authentication system without writing any authentication code yourself. Everything is pre-built and secure.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="simplified-section">
        <h2 class="text-center">How Authentication Works in .NET</h2>
        
        <div class="process-flow">
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-circle">
                    <div class="step-number">1</div>
                </div>
                <h4>Project Creation</h4>
                <p>When creating your project, you select "Individual Accounts" as the authentication type.</p>
                <div class="visual-guide">
                    <div class="visual-box">
                        <strong>Visual Studio / .NET CLI</strong>
                        <p>Select: Individual Accounts</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="process-arrow">→</div>
            
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-circle">
                    <div class="step-number">2</div>
                </div>
                <h4>Auto-Generated Code</h4>
                <p>.NET automatically creates all the authentication code you need:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Registration pages</li>
                    <li>Login pages</li>
                    <li>Password reset</li>
                    <li>Email confirmation</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="process-arrow">→</div>
            
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-circle">
                    <div class="step-number">3</div>
                </div>
                <h4>Database Setup</h4>
                <p>All necessary database tables are created automatically:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>User accounts table</li>
                    <li>Password hashes</li>
                    <li>Login sessions</li>
                    <li>Security tokens</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="process-arrow">→</div>
            
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-circle">
                    <div class="step-number">4</div>
                </div>
                <h4>Ready to Use</h4>
                <p>Your application now has complete authentication:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Users can register</li>
                    <li>Users can login/logout</li>
                    <li>Passwords are secured</li>
                    <li>Sessions are managed</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="authentication-components">
        <h2>What You Get With Individual Accounts</h2>
        <p>When you select "Individual Accounts" authentication, here's everything that's included:</p>
        
