                    <li>Run your application</li>
                    <li>Look for "Register" and "Login" links in the navigation</li>
                    <li>Click Register and create a test account</li>
                    <li>Log out and log back in with your credentials</li>
                    <li>Try accessing a protected page (like the Privacy page if you add <code>[Authorize]</code>)</li>
                </ol>
                <p>If all these work, your authentication system is fully functional.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="authentication-vs-authorization">
        <h2>Authentication vs Authorization: Understanding the Difference</h2>
        
        <div class="comparison">
            <div class="auth-type">
                <h3>Authentication</h3>
                <p class="subtitle">(What we're covering now)</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Question:</strong> Who are you?</li>
                    <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Verifying identity</li>
                    <li><strong>Example:</strong> Login with username/password</li>
                    <li><strong>Result:</strong> System knows who you are</li>
                    <li><strong>Code:</strong> Built-in with Individual Accounts</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="key-point">
                    <strong>Authentication = Identity Verification</strong>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="separator">
                <div class="vs-circle">VS</div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="auth-type">
                <h3>Authorization</h3>
                <p class="subtitle">(Coming next)</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Question:</strong> What can you do?</li>
                    <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Checking permissions</li>
                    <li><strong>Example:</strong> Can you access admin pages?</li>
                    <li><strong>Result:</strong> System knows what you're allowed to do</li>
                    <li><strong>Code:</strong> Uses roles and policies</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="key-point">
                    <strong>Authorization = Permission Checking</strong>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="simple-analogy">
            <h4>Simple Analogy</h4>
            <p><strong>Authentication</strong> is like checking someone's ID to enter a building. <strong>Authorization</strong> is like checking if they have access to the executive floor once they're inside.</p>
            <p>With .NET Individual Accounts, authentication is done. You'll learn about authorization (controlling what authenticated users can do) in the next section.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="customization-note">
        <h3>Important: You Can Still Customize</h3>
        <p>While .NET provides complete authentication out of the box, you can still customize it:</p>
        <div class="customization-grid">
            <div class="custom-option">
                <h5>Add Custom User Fields</h5>
                <p>Add properties like FirstName, LastName, ProfilePicture to the user model</p>
            </div>
            <div class="custom-option">
                <h5>Modify Password Rules</h5>
                <p>Change password length or complexity requirements</p>
            </div>
            <div class="custom-option">
                <h5>Customize Email Templates</h5>
                <p>Change the look and content of confirmation emails</p>
            </div>
            <div class="custom-option">
                <h5>Add Social Logins</h5>
                <p>Enable login with Google, Facebook, or other providers</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3"><strong>The key point:</strong> You start with a complete, working system and only customize what you need to change.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quiz-section">
        <h3>Quick Check: Authentication Understanding</h3>
        <div class="quiz-question">
            <p><strong>Question:</strong> What does selecting "Individual Accounts" authentication give you?</p>
            
            <div class="quiz-options">
                <button class="quiz-option" data-correct="true">
